      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are correct that the evidence on wage suppression is often debated, and much of the academic literature suggests that the impact is generally small and concentrated within very specific, low-skilled sectors. While some fears of direct wage depression persist in political discourse, many economists argue that immigrants complement the workforce rather than directly competing with native-born workers across the board. Overall, the consensus among many mainstream studies is that the net effect on overall wages is minimal, while the benefits of increased labor supply are more consistently documented.",
      "source": "target",
